eration,", "tokens": [51380, 400, 321, 603, 751, 807, 439, 264, 4439, 300, 436, 352, 807, 337, 264, 16743, 399, 5125, 11, 51666], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.24370799504273327, "compression_ratio": 1.6984615384615385, "no_speech_prob": 0.010768304578959942}, {"id": 37, "seek": 8576, "start": 111.80000000000001, "end": 112.80000000000001, "text": " correlation of logs.", "tokens": [51666, 20009, 295, 20820, 13, 51716], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.24370799504273327, "compression_ratio": 1.6984615384615385, "no_speech_prob": 0.010768304578959942}, {"id": 38, "seek": 8576, "start": 112.80000000000001, "end": 115.64, "text": " We'll talk about that later on.", "tokens": [51716, 492, 603, 751, 466, 300, 1780, 322, 13, 51858], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.24370799504273327, "compression_ratio": 1.6984615384615385, "no_speech_prob": 0.010768304578959942}, {"id": 39, "seek": 11564, "start": 115.64, "end": 120.72, "text": " For now, let's just say that when it comes to where can we collect a log event data from", "tokens": [50364, 1171, 586, 11, 718, 311, 445, 584, 300, 562, 309, 1487, 281, 689, 393, 321, 2500, 257, 3565, 2280, 1412, 490, 50618], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14119104828153337, "compression_ratio": 1.7099236641221374, "no_speech_prob": 0.0004430475237313658}, {"id": 40, "seek": 11564, "start": 120.72, "end": 121.72, "text": " everywhere?", "tokens": [50618, 5315, 30, 50668], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14119104828153337, "compression_ratio": 1.7099236641221374, "no_speech_prob": 0.0004430475237313658}, {"id": 41, "seek": 11564, "start": 121.72, "end": 122.72, "text": " And what do we want to do?", "tokens": [50668, 400, 437, 360, 321, 528, 281, 360, 30, 50718], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14119104828153337, "compression_ratio": 1.7099236641221374, "no_speech_prob": 0.0004430475237313658}, {"id": 42, "seek": 11564, "start": 122.72, "end": 127.04, "text": " We want to pull all that data into our log correlation system into one central system so", "tokens": [50718, 492, 528, 281, 2235, 439, 300, 1412, 666, 527, 3565, 20009, 1185, 666, 472, 5777, 1185, 370, 50934], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14119104828153337, "compression_ratio": 1.7099236641221374, "no_speech_prob": 0.0004430475237313658}, {"id": 43, "seek": 11564, "start": 127.04, "end": 134.56, "text": " that we can then analyze that data, look for the proverbial needle and a stack of needles.", "tokens": [50934, 300, 321, 393, 550, 12477, 300, 1412, 11, 574, 337, 264, 49923, 831, 11037, 293, 257, 8630, 295, 24792, 13, 51310], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14119104828153337, "compression_ratio": 1.7099236641221374, "no_speech_prob": 0.0004430475237313658}, {"id": 44, "seek": 11564, "start": 134.56, "end": 140.36, "text": " One of the problems we face when logging is our endpoint devices, things like our firewalls,", "tokens": [51310, 1485, 295, 264, 2740, 321, 1851, 562, 27991, 307, 527, 35795, 5759, 11, 721, 411, 527, 36109, 82, 11, 51600], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14119104828153337, "compression_ratio": 1.7099236641221374, "no_speech_prob": 0.0004430475237313658}, {"id": 45, "seek": 11564, "start": 140.36, "end": 143.0, "text": " can produce an enormous amount of logging data.", "tokens": [51600, 393, 5258, 364, 11322, 2372, 295, 27991, 1412, 13, 51732], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14119104828153337, "compression_ratio": 1.7099236641221374, "no_speech_prob": 0.0004430475237313658}, {"id": 46, "seek": 14300, "start": 143.0, "end": 146.04, "text": " But they typically have very limited storage on board.", "tokens": [50364, 583, 436, 5850, 362, 588, 5567, 6725, 322, 3150, 13, 50516], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13230648534051304, "compression_ratio": 1.6942446043165467, "no_speech_prob": 0.012021660804748535}, {"id": 47, "seek": 14300, "start": 146.04, "end": 151.12, "text": " And so if we have a requirement to keep a huge amount of logging data, it's often difficult", "tokens": [50516, 400, 370, 498, 321, 362, 257, 11695, 281, 1066, 257, 2603, 2372, 295, 27991, 1412, 11, 309, 311, 2049, 2252, 50770], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13230648534051304, "compression_ratio": 1.6942446043165467, "no_speech_prob": 0.012021660804748535}, {"id": 48, "seek": 14300, "start": 151.12, "end": 153.48, "text": " or impossible to do that on the endpoint.", "tokens": [50770, 420, 6243, 281, 360, 300, 322, 264, 35795, 13, 50888], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13230648534051304, "compression_ratio": 1.6942446043165467, "no_speech_prob": 0.012021660804748535}, {"id": 49, "seek": 14300, "start": 153.48, "end": 157.72, "text": " So let's talk about a couple of methods of how we can limit log file sizes.", "tokens": [50888, 407, 718, 311, 751, 466, 257, 1916, 295, 7150, 295, 577, 321, 393, 4948, 3565, 3991, 11602, 13, 51100], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13230648534051304, "compression_ratio": 1.6942446043165467, "no_speech_prob": 0.012021660804748535}, {"id": 50, "seek": 14300, "start": 157.72, "end": 162.08, "text": " Two major methods that you need to know about, circular overwrite and clipping levels.", "tokens": [51100, 4453, 2563, 7150, 300, 291, 643, 281, 458, 466, 11, 16476, 670, 21561, 293, 49320, 4358, 13, 51318], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13230648534051304, "compression_ratio": 1.6942446043165467, "no_speech_prob": 0.012021660804748535}, {"id": 51, "seek": 14300, "start": 162.08, "end": 164.8, "text": " Now let's start with circular overwrite.", "tokens": [51318, 823, 718, 311, 722, 365, 16476, 670, 21561, 13, 51454], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13230648534051304, "compression_ratio": 1.6942446043165467, "no_speech_prob": 0.012021660804748535}, {"id": 52, "seek": 14300, "start": 164.8, "end": 170.16, "text": " The way circular overwrite works is you set a maximum log file size or length.", "tokens": [51454, 440, 636, 16476, 670, 21561, 1985, 307, 291, 992, 257, 6674, 3565, 3991, 2744, 420, 4641, 13, 51722], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13230648534051304, "compression_ratio": 1.6942446043165467, "no_speech_prob": 0.012021660804748535}, {"id": 53, "seek": 17016, "start": 170.16, "end": 176.2, "text": " And then you start writing log event data until you reach the maximum file size or the", "tokens": [50364, 400, 550, 291, 722, 3579, 3565, 2280, 1412, 1826, 291, 2524, 264, 6674, 3991, 2744, 420, 264, 50666], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13900448104082527, "compression_ratio": 2.0762711864406778, "no_speech_prob": 0.0008700283942744136}, {"id": 54, "seek": 17016, "start": 176.2, "end": 181.12, "text": " maximum number of lines and then you circle back to the top and start overwriting.", "tokens": [50666, 6674, 1230, 295, 3876, 293, 550, 291, 6329, 646, 281, 264, 1192, 293, 722, 670, 19868, 13, 50912], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13900448104082527, "compression_ratio": 2.0762711864406778, "no_speech_prob": 0.0008700283942744136}, {"id": 55, "seek": 17016, "start": 181.12, "end": 183.51999999999998, "text": " That's circular overwrite.", "tokens": [50912, 663, 311, 16476, 670, 21561, 13, 51032], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13900448104082527, "compression_ratio": 2.0762711864406778, "no_speech_prob": 0.0008700283942744136}, {"id": 56, "seek": 17016, "start": 183.51999999999998, "end": 187.16, "text": " And what it means is that your log file size is never ending at larger than the maximum", "tokens": [51032, 400, 437, 309, 1355, 307, 300, 428, 3565, 3991, 2744, 307, 1128, 8121, 412, 4833, 813, 264, 6674, 51214], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13900448104082527, "compression_ratio": 2.0762711864406778, "no_speech_prob": 0.0008700283942744136}, {"id": 57, "seek": 17016, "start": 187.16, "end": 191.88, "text": " number of entries or the file size that you set because as soon as you reach that maximum,", "tokens": [51214, 1230, 295, 23041, 420, 264, 3991, 2744, 300, 291, 992, 570, 382, 2321, 382, 291, 2524, 300, 6674, 11, 51450], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13900448104082527, "compression_ratio": 2.0762711864406778, "no_speech_prob": 0.0008700283942744136}, {"id": 58, "seek": 17016, "start": 191.88, "end": 195.2, "text": " you circle back to the top and start overwriting.", "tokens": [51450, 291, 6329, 646, 281, 264, 1192, 293, 722, 670, 19868, 13, 51616], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13900448104082527, "compression_ratio": 2.0762711864406778, "no_speech_prob": 0.0008700283942744136}, {"id": 59, "seek": 17016, "start": 195.2, "end": 199.07999999999998, "text": " The other method you can use is what's known as clipping levels.", "tokens": [51616, 440, 661, 3170, 291, 393, 764, 307, 437, 311, 2570, 382, 49320, 4358, 13, 51810], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13900448104082527, "compression_ratio": 2.0762711864406778, "no_speech_prob": 0.0008700283942744136}, {"id": 60, "seek": 19908, "start": 199.08, "end": 203.20000000000002, "text": " When clipping levels is this idea that we set a threshold below that threshold, don't", "tokens": [50364, 1133, 49320, 4358, 307, 341, 1558, 300, 321, 992, 257, 14678, 2507, 300, 14678, 11, 500, 380, 50570], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19771026162540212, "compression_ratio": 1.7174721189591078, "no_speech_prob": 0.004034505225718021}, {"id": 61, "seek": 19908, "start": 203.20000000000002, "end": 204.72, "text": " bother logging anything.", "tokens": [50570, 8677, 27991, 1340, 13, 50646], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19771026162540212, "compression_ratio": 1.7174721189591078, "no_speech_prob": 0.004034505225718021}, {"id": 62, "seek": 19908, "start": 204.72, "end": 207.12, "text": " Above that threshold, start logging.", "tokens": [50646, 32691, 300, 14678, 11, 722, 27991, 13, 50766], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19771026162540212, "compression_ratio": 1.7174721189591078, "no_speech_prob": 0.004034505225718021}, {"id": 63, "seek": 19908, "start": 207.12, "end": 209.88000000000002, "text": " Here's an example.", "tokens": [50766, 1692, 311, 364, 1365, 13, 50904], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19771026162540212, "compression_ratio": 1.7174721189591078, "no_speech_prob": 0.004034505225718021}, {"id": 64, "seek": 19908, "start": 209.88000000000002, "end": 212.56, "text": " Failed or incorrect passwords.", "tokens": [50904, 479, 24731, 420, 18424, 33149, 13, 51038], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19771026162540212, "compression_ratio": 1.7174721189591078, "no_speech_prob": 0.004034505225718021}, {"id": 65, "seek": 19908, "start": 212.56, "end": 217.20000000000002, "text": " So when I change my password for the first month or first week anyways, I type in the", "tokens": [51038, 407, 562, 286, 1319, 452, 11524, 337, 264, 700, 1618, 420, 700, 1243, 13448, 11, 286, 2010, 294, 264, 51270], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19771026162540212, "compression_ratio": 1.7174721189591078, "no_speech_prob": 0.004034505225718021}, {"id": 66, "seek": 19908, "start": 217.20000000000002, "end": 220.24, "text": " wrong password and it's a failed log event.", "tokens": [51270, 2085, 11524, 293, 309, 311, 257, 7612, 3565, 2280, 13, 51422], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19771026162540212, "compression_ratio": 1.7174721189591078, "no_speech_prob": 0.004034505225718021}, {"id": 67, "seek": 19908, "start": 220.24, "end": 222.48000000000002, "text": " This happens all the time for people.", "tokens": [51422, 639, 2314, 439, 264, 565, 337, 561, 13, 51534], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19771026162540212, "compression_ratio": 1.7174721189591078, "no_speech_prob": 0.004034505225718021}, {"id": 68, "seek": 19908, "start": 222.48000000000002, "end": 227.44, "text": " And so the vast majority of the time, if you see one failed log in attempt, it's not concerning.", "tokens": [51534, 400, 370, 264, 8369, 6286, 295, 264, 565, 11, 498, 291, 536, 472, 7612, 3565, 294, 5217, 11, 309, 311, 406, 18087, 13, 51782], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19771026162540212, "compression_ratio": 1.7174721189591078, "no_speech_prob": 0.004034505225718021}, {"id": 69, "seek": 22744, "start": 227.44, "end": 230.96, "text": " So you might set a threshold and you would say, you know what, below say three failed log", "tokens": [50364, 407, 291, 1062, 992, 257, 14678, 293, 291, 576, 584, 11, 291, 458, 437, 11, 2507, 584, 1045, 7612, 3565, 50540], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1569400425374943, "compression_ratio": 1.8163934426229509, "no_speech_prob": 0.001329083926975727}, {"id": 70, "seek": 22744, "start": 230.96, "end": 234.32, "text": " in attempts in 30 seconds or not going to log anything.", "tokens": [50540, 294, 15257, 294, 2217, 3949, 420, 406, 516, 281, 3565, 1340, 13, 50708], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1569400425374943, "compression_ratio": 1.8163934426229509, "no_speech_prob": 0.001329083926975727}, {"id": 71, "seek": 22744, "start": 234.32, "end": 238.44, "text": " So all those times that people are just fat fingering their password or forgetting their", "tokens": [50708, 407, 439, 729, 1413, 300, 561, 366, 445, 4046, 3823, 1794, 641, 11524, 420, 25428, 641, 50914], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1569400425374943, "compression_ratio": 1.8163934426229509, "no_speech_prob": 0.001329083926975727}, {"id": 72, "seek": 22744, "start": 238.44, "end": 240.96, "text": " password, you're not logging any of that.", "tokens": [50914, 11524, 11, 291, 434, 406, 27991, 604, 295, 300, 13, 51040], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1569400425374943, "compression_ratio": 1.8163934426229509, "no_speech_prob": 0.001329083926975727}, {"id": 73, "seek": 22744, "start": 240.96, "end": 245.32, "text": " But if you suddenly see like 50 failed log in attempts within 30 seconds, should you be", "tokens": [51040, 583, 498, 291, 5800, 536, 411, 2625, 7612, 3565, 294, 15257, 1951, 2217, 3949, 11, 820, 291, 312, 51258], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1569400425374943, "compression_ratio": 1.8163934426229509, "no_speech_prob": 0.001329083926975727}, {"id": 74, "seek": 22744, "start": 245.32, "end": 246.32, "text": " logging that?", "tokens": [51258, 27991, 300, 30, 51308], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1569400425374943, "compression_ratio": 1.8163934426229509, "no_speech_prob": 0.001329083926975727}, {"id": 75, "seek": 22744, "start": 246.32, "end": 247.32, "text": " Absolutely.", "tokens": [51308, 7021, 13, 51358], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1569400425374943, "compression_ratio": 1.8163934426229509, "no_speech_prob": 0.001329083926975727}, {"id": 76, "seek": 22744, "start": 247.32, "end": 250.2, "text": " That's probably someone trying to brute force your system.", "tokens": [51358, 663, 311, 1391, 1580, 1382, 281, 47909, 3464, 428, 1185, 13, 51502], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1569400425374943, "compression_ratio": 1.8163934426229509, "no_speech_prob": 0.001329083926975727}, {"id": 77, "seek": 22744, "start": 250.2, "end": 251.76, "text": " And so that's the idea of clipping levels.", "tokens": [51502, 400, 370, 300, 311, 264, 1558, 295, 49320, 4358, 13, 51580], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1569400425374943, "compression_ratio": 1.8163934426229509, "no_speech_prob": 0.001329083926975727}, {"id": 78, "seek": 22744, "start": 251.76, "end": 255.24, "text": " You set a threshold below that threshold, don't log anything.", "tokens": [51580, 509, 992, 257, 14678, 2507, 300, 14678, 11, 500, 380, 3565, 1340, 13, 51754], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1569400425374943, "compression_ratio": 1.8163934426229509, "no_speech_prob": 0.001329083926975727}, {"id": 79, "seek": 25524, "start": 255.24, "end": 258.36, "text": " Love that threshold, start logging.", "tokens": [50364, 5956, 300, 14678, 11, 722, 27991, 13, 50520], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.18041622129260984, "compression_ratio": 1.8565400843881856, "no_speech_prob": 0.014365392737090588}, {"id": 80, "seek": 25524, "start": 258.36, "end": 260.32, "text": " Here's a good question.", "tokens": [50520, 1692, 311, 257, 665, 1168, 13, 50618], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.18041622129260984, "compression_ratio": 1.8565400843881856, "no_speech_prob": 0.014365392737090588}, {"id": 81, "seek": 25524, "start": 260.32, "end": 265.48, "text": " Which of these methods, circular overwrite or clipping levels, would be better if you", "tokens": [50618, 3013, 295, 613, 7150, 11, 16476, 670, 21561, 420, 49320, 4358, 11, 576, 312, 1101, 498, 291, 50876], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.18041622129260984, "compression_ratio": 1.8565400843881856, "no_speech_prob": 0.014365392737090588}, {"id": 82, "seek": 25524, "start": 265.48, "end": 269.48, "text": " wanted to detect a breach?", "tokens": [50876, 1415, 281, 5531, 257, 31086, 30, 51076], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.18041622129260984, "compression_ratio": 1.8565400843881856, "no_speech_prob": 0.014365392737090588}, {"id": 83, "seek": 25524, "start": 269.48, "end": 271.32, "text": " And the answer is clipping levels.", "tokens": [51076, 400, 264, 1867, 307, 49320, 4358, 13, 51168], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.18041622129260984, "compression_ratio": 1.8565400843881856, "no_speech_prob": 0.014365392737090588}, {"id": 84, "seek": 25524, "start": 271.32, "end": 274.88, "text": " And the reason is that with circular overwrite, if you want to investigate a breach, you need", "tokens": [51168, 400, 264, 1778, 307, 300, 365, 16476, 670, 21561, 11, 498, 291, 528, 281, 15013, 257, 31086, 11, 291, 643, 51346], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.18041622129260984, "compression_ratio": 1.8565400843881856, "no_speech_prob": 0.014365392737090588}, {"id": 85, "seek": 25524, "start": 274.88, "end": 275.88, "text": " the log data.", "tokens": [51346, 264, 3565, 1412, 13, 51396], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.18041622129260984, "compression_ratio": 1.8565400843881856, "no_speech_prob": 0.014365392737090588}, {"id": 86, "seek": 25524, "start": 275.88, "end": 280.40000000000003, "text": " And in circular overwrite, you're erasing your log data, data, you're overwriting your", "tokens": [51396, 400, 294, 16476, 670, 21561, 11, 291, 434, 1189, 3349, 428, 3565, 1412, 11, 1412, 11, 291, 434, 670, 19868, 428, 51622], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.18041622129260984, "compression_ratio": 1.8565400843881856, "no_speech_prob": 0.014365392737090588}, {"id": 87, "seek": 25524, "start": 280.40000000000003, "end": 282.28000000000003, "text": " data once you get to a certain point.", "tokens": [51622, 1412, 1564, 291, 483, 281, 257, 1629, 935, 13, 51716], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.18041622129260984, "compression_ratio": 1.8565400843881856, "no_speech_prob": 0.014365392737090588}, {"id": 88, "seek": 28228, "start": 282.28, "end": 285.84, "text": " Whereas with clipping levels, you're limiting the amount of data, but you're not ever", "tokens": [50364, 13813, 365, 49320, 4358, 11, 291, 434, 22083, 264, 2372, 295, 1412, 11, 457, 291, 434, 406, 1562, 50542], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15014925620538724, "compression_ratio": 1.771523178807947, "no_speech_prob": 0.019979456439614296}, {"id": 89, "seek": 28228, "start": 285.84, "end": 286.84, "text": " overwriting it.", "tokens": [50542, 670, 19868, 309, 13, 50592], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15014925620538724, "compression_ratio": 1.771523178807947, "no_speech_prob": 0.019979456439614296}, {"id": 90, "seek": 28228, "start": 286.84, "end": 290.64, "text": " So if you get a question like that, the better type of logging, of a better method of", "tokens": [50592, 407, 498, 291, 483, 257, 1168, 411, 300, 11, 264, 1101, 2010, 295, 27991, 11, 295, 257, 1101, 3170, 295, 50782], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15014925620538724, "compression_ratio": 1.771523178807947, "no_speech_prob": 0.019979456439614296}, {"id": 91, "seek": 28228, "start": 290.64, "end": 296.28, "text": " limiting log file sizes, if you're looking for a breach, is clipping levels.", "tokens": [50782, 22083, 3565, 3991, 11602, 11, 498, 291, 434, 1237, 337, 257, 31086, 11, 307, 49320, 4358, 13, 51064], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15014925620538724, "compression_ratio": 1.771523178807947, "no_speech_prob": 0.019979456439614296}, {"id": 92, "seek": 28228, "start": 296.28, "end": 299.32, "text": " Final part about logging here that I want to mention.", "tokens": [51064, 13443, 644, 466, 27991, 510, 300, 286, 528, 281, 2152, 13, 51216], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15014925620538724, "compression_ratio": 1.771523178807947, "no_speech_prob": 0.019979456439614296}, {"id": 93, "seek": 28228, "start": 299.32, "end": 303.52, "text": " And this relates to the time that we attach to a log file.", "tokens": [51216, 400, 341, 16155, 281, 264, 565, 300, 321, 5085, 281, 257, 3565, 3991, 13, 51426], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15014925620538724, "compression_ratio": 1.771523178807947, "no_speech_prob": 0.019979456439614296}, {"id": 94, "seek": 28228, "start": 303.52, "end": 305.32, "text": " You want to have consistent timestamps.", "tokens": [51426, 509, 528, 281, 362, 8398, 49108, 23150, 13, 51516], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15014925620538724, "compression_ratio": 1.771523178807947, "no_speech_prob": 0.019979456439614296}, {"id": 95, "seek": 28228, "start": 305.32, "end": 309.96, "text": " I'm going to talk later on in the SIM system about how if you want to correlate events,", "tokens": [51516, 286, 478, 516, 281, 751, 1780, 322, 294, 264, 24738, 1185, 466, 577, 498, 291, 528, 281, 48742, 3931, 11, 51748], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15014925620538724, "compression_ratio": 1.771523178807947, "no_speech_prob": 0.019979456439614296}, {"id": 96, "seek": 28228, "start": 309.96, "end": 311.2, "text": " line them up with each other.", "tokens": [51748, 1622, 552, 493, 365, 1184, 661, 13, 51810], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15014925620538724, "compression_ratio": 1.771523178807947, "no_speech_prob": 0.019979456439614296}, {"id": 97, "seek": 31120, "start": 311.2, "end": 313.4, "text": " You need to have consistent timestamps.", "tokens": [50364, 509, 643, 281, 362, 8398, 49108, 23150, 13, 50474], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19758814031427557, "compression_ratio": 1.7265625, "no_speech_prob": 0.07145259529352188}, {"id": 98, "seek": 31120, "start": 313.4, "end": 318.14, "text": " Has to be the same date, you know, same year, month, day, format, same, 12 or 25 hour", "tokens": [50474, 8646, 281, 312, 264, 912, 4002, 11, 291, 458, 11, 912, 1064, 11, 1618, 11, 786, 11, 7877, 11, 912, 11, 2272, 420, 3552, 1773, 50711], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19758814031427557, "compression_ratio": 1.7265625, "no_speech_prob": 0.07145259529352188}, {"id": 99, "seek": 31120, "start": 318.14, "end": 321.44, "text": " clock format, whatever it is, make it consistent.", "tokens": [50711, 7830, 7877, 11, 2035, 309, 307, 11, 652, 309, 8398, 13, 50876], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19758814031427557, "compression_ratio": 1.7265625, "no_speech_prob": 0.07145259529352188}, {"id": 100, "seek": 31120, "start": 321.44, "end": 326.24, "text": " The final piece is all of the systems in your environment need to have the same system", "tokens": [50876, 440, 2572, 2522, 307, 439, 295, 264, 3652, 294, 428, 2823, 643, 281, 362, 264, 912, 1185, 51116], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19758814031427557, "compression_ratio": 1.7265625, "no_speech_prob": 0.07145259529352188}, {"id": 101, "seek": 31120, "start": 326.24, "end": 327.24, "text": " time.", "tokens": [51116, 565, 13, 51166], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19758814031427557, "compression_ratio": 1.7265625, "no_speech_prob": 0.07145259529352188}, {"id": 102, "seek": 31120, "start": 327.24, "end": 331.2, "text": " If you want to be able to trace, track, how in a tracker, how an attacker traversed your", "tokens": [51166, 759, 291, 528, 281, 312, 1075, 281, 13508, 11, 2837, 11, 577, 294, 257, 37516, 11, 577, 364, 35871, 23149, 292, 428, 51364], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19758814031427557, "compression_ratio": 1.7265625, "no_speech_prob": 0.07145259529352188}, {"id": 103, "seek": 31120, "start": 331.2, "end": 335.32, "text": " network, got into different systems, got a foothold here and then moved there, it is", "tokens": [51364, 3209, 11, 658, 666, 819, 3652, 11, 658, 257, 726, 900, 2641, 510, 293, 550, 4259, 456, 11, 309, 307, 51570], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19758814031427557, "compression_ratio": 1.7265625, "no_speech_prob": 0.07145259529352188}, {"id": 104, "seek": 33532, "start": 335.32, "end": 341.44, "text": " very difficult to trace and figure out exactly what someone did, an attacker did, if your", "tokens": [50364, 588, 2252, 281, 13508, 293, 2573, 484, 2293, 437, 1580, 630, 11, 364, 35871, 630, 11, 498, 428, 50670], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.18500616791051464, "compression_ratio": 1.7821011673151752, "no_speech_prob": 0.016975484788417816}, {"id": 105, "seek": 33532, "start": 341.44, "end": 345.71999999999997, "text": " systems have different clock times, if this one's five seconds faster, that one's three", "tokens": [50670, 3652, 362, 819, 7830, 1413, 11, 498, 341, 472, 311, 1732, 3949, 4663, 11, 300, 472, 311, 1045, 50884], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.18500616791051464, "compression_ratio": 1.7821011673151752, "no_speech_prob": 0.016975484788417816}, {"id": 106, "seek": 33532, "start": 345.71999999999997, "end": 349.4, "text": " seconds slower, it becomes very difficult to trace events.", "tokens": [50884, 3949, 14009, 11, 309, 3643, 588, 2252, 281, 13508, 3931, 13, 51068], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.18500616791051464, "compression_ratio": 1.7821011673151752, "no_speech_prob": 0.016975484788417816}, {"id": 107, "seek": 33532, "start": 349.4, "end": 354.24, "text": " And so the way that we can make sure that all of our systems, clocks are aligned is through", "tokens": [51068, 400, 370, 264, 636, 300, 321, 393, 652, 988, 300, 439, 295, 527, 3652, 11, 41528, 366, 17962, 307, 807, 51310], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.18500616791051464, "compression_ratio": 1.7821011673151752, "no_speech_prob": 0.016975484788417816}, {"id": 108, "seek": 33532, "start": 354.24, "end": 358.64, "text": " the MNTP protocol, network time protocol.", "tokens": [51310, 264, 376, 45, 16804, 10336, 11, 3209, 565, 10336, 13, 51530], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.18500616791051464, "compression_ratio": 1.7821011673151752, "no_speech_prob": 0.016975484788417816}, {"id": 109, "seek": 33532, "start": 358.64, "end": 364.24, "text": " And as the name implies, this protocol allows a server to synchronize its system clock.", "tokens": [51530, 400, 382, 264, 1315, 18779, 11, 341, 10336, 4045, 257, 7154, 281, 19331, 1125, 1080, 1185, 7830, 13, 51810], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.18500616791051464, "compression_ratio": 1.7821011673151752, "no_speech_prob": 0.016975484788417816}, {"id": 110, "seek": 36424, "start": 364.24, "end": 368.52, "text": " And there are basically what you can connect with this is an atomic clock.", "tokens": [50364, 400, 456, 366, 1936, 437, 291, 393, 1745, 365, 341, 307, 364, 22275, 7830, 13, 50578], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1934023984928721, "compression_ratio": 1.9272727272727272, "no_speech_prob": 0.0005818348727189004}, {"id": 111, "seek": 36424, "start": 368.52, "end": 372.08, "text": " And through the MNTP protocol, you can synchronize your system clock with one of these world", "tokens": [50578, 400, 807, 264, 376, 45, 16804, 10336, 11, 291, 393, 19331, 1125, 428, 1185, 7830, 365, 472, 295, 613, 1002, 50756], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1934023984928721, "compression_ratio": 1.9272727272727272, "no_speech_prob": 0.0005818348727189004}, {"id": 112, "seek": 36424, "start": 372.08, "end": 376.40000000000003, "text": " atomic clocks through NASA or other US agencies and other agencies around the world.", "tokens": [50756, 22275, 41528, 807, 12077, 420, 661, 2546, 9504, 293, 661, 9504, 926, 264, 1002, 13, 50972], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1934023984928721, "compression_ratio": 1.9272727272727272, "no_speech_prob": 0.0005818348727189004}, {"id": 113, "seek": 36424, "start": 376.40000000000003, "end": 380.3, "text": " And if every system in your environment is using the MNTP to synchronize the system", "tokens": [50972, 400, 498, 633, 1185, 294, 428, 2823, 307, 1228, 264, 376, 45, 16804, 281, 19331, 1125, 264, 1185, 51167], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1934023984928721, "compression_ratio": 1.9272727272727272, "no_speech_prob": 0.0005818348727189004}, {"id": 114, "seek": 36424, "start": 380.3, "end": 384.44, "text": " clock, all the servers in the environment, all the systems in the environment will have", "tokens": [51167, 7830, 11, 439, 264, 15909, 294, 264, 2823, 11, 439, 264, 3652, 294, 264, 2823, 486, 362, 51374], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1934023984928721, "compression_ratio": 1.9272727272727272, "no_speech_prob": 0.0005818348727189004}, {"id": 115, "seek": 38444, "start": 384.44, "end": 385.44, "text": " the exact same time.", "tokens": [50366, 264, 1900, 912, 565, 13, 50414], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.8557217717170715, "compression_ratio": 0.7142857142857143, "no_speech_prob": 0.6708298325538635}], "language": "en"}